The folks at Hauser & Wirth want you to experience the art
collecting lifestyle in a down-to-earth, casual setting, complete with a ve=
ry mindful seasonal locavore menu. Can a simple concept of art gallery-as-r=
estaurant bring new collectors into the fold?

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

After a day spent trudging from gallery to gallery, and with a
couple of hours to kill before dinner, Mrs. Wallpower and I stopped in SoHo=
 a couple weeks ago for a holiday drink at Manuela, the Hauser & Wirth rest=
aurant that opened at Prince and Wooster in late October. Our companion, a =
glamorous young art advisor, had spent the day packing for a multi-leg holi=
day jaunt to Paris and England to meet her vaguely aristocratic (and newish=
) boyfriend and his family. Together, the three of us were the exact target=
 clientele for Manuela, where the vibe is meant to
be =E2=80=9Cart-world hangout,=E2=80=9D and where industry players (the gla=
morous art advisor) rub shoulders with the curious (me and my wife) and the=
 aspirational (most of the folks at the bar).=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Manuela is designed to serve as =E2=80=9Ca democratic space that doesn=E2=
=80=99t feel like it has the pomp and ceremony that some places have,=E2=80=
=9D Bee Emmott, the C.E.O. of Artfarm, Hauser=E2=80=99s sister hospitality =
company,
told ( https://www.vogue.com/article/manuela-restaurant-artfarm-soho-nyc?ut=
m_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) Vogue. Presumably she was ta=
lking about other restaurants, but you could apply the same sentiment to th=
e entire gallery world, where self-serious is the default mode, and where e=
veryone claims to want new clients, but remains wary of investing time and =
manners into anyone who hasn=E2=80=99t already demonstrated commitment to t=
he game. Here, though, all
it takes is a reservation to grant you proximity to the world of serious ar=
t collecting.

=C2=A0

A similar idea drives Artfarm, Hauser=E2=80=99s extensive program to make a=
rt less remote and foreboding by pairing it with hospitality. Strategically=
, combining art and hospitality=E2=80=94from the gallery side=E2=80=94has b=
een one of the few new business innovations in art dealing since the emerge=
nce of the global gallery decades ago. Hauser=E2=80=99s own
expansion ( https://www.ft.com/content/323ea74d-827e-4f62-a08e-457e61e19ab5=
?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWal=
l+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) into food and lodging bega=
n with a Somerset, U.K., farm and gallery. Artfarm also now runs the Grouch=
o Club, in London, as well as restaurants and hotels in multiple locations,=
 combining the experience of food, art, and travel. These include the origi=
nal Manuela, which opened in the Hauser & Wirth complex in Los Angeles in 2=
016; restaurants and pubs in London
and Somerset; plus destinations in Scotland and Minorca. There are also pla=
ns for a Groucho Club near the Yorkshire sculpture park, where there=E2=80=
=99s already a branch of Soho House. (The Wirths=E2=80=94husband and wife p=
artners Iwan and Manuela=E2=80=94aren=E2=80=99t the only ones hip to the ap=
peal of art as a travel beacon.)=C2=A0

Manuela
restaurant

By making art more of an everyday experience, Artfarm is
essentially doing the reverse of what Peter Marino did with a slew of fashi=
on boutiques and the flagship Tiffany store. There, the architect used art =
to make clothes and handbags seem loftier and more refined=E2=80=94i.e., no=
t just very expensive consumer goods: They were now art-adjacent, artlike, =
or just plain art. Artfarm, by contrast, is making art less intimidating an=
d inscrutable, safer for consumption.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The commercial logic here is straightforward, even if it=E2=80=99s not the =
only reasoning: There=E2=80=99s a new generation of potential art buyers wh=
o have to get used to these objects, and who, while they can afford the lux=
ury travel and hospitality, find the idea of ownership too remote in a soci=
al sense, or too aspirational in a financial sense. And, maybe more importa=
ntly and less obviously, Hauser & Wirth is building a potentially valuable =
business off
the untapped resource of the gallery=E2=80=99s stable of artists, estates, =
and their inventory.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At Manuela, as at other Artfarm restaurants, museum/gallery quality art is =
hanging on the walls, up close and personal. At, say, the Met, you might st=
roll by Both, a Philip Guston donated ( https://www.metmuseum.org/art/colle=
ction/search/894031?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%2=
9&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Dem=
ail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) by the =
artist=E2=80=99s daughter, glance at the wall tag and, if you=E2=80=99re lu=
cky and diligent, linger a few minutes. At Manuela, though, you might be se=
ated right under Crescent, a work by the same artist, of similar size and c=
omposition, completed just before Both in 1976=E2=80=94or maybe under the C=
indy Sherman centerfold ( https://www.artic.edu/artworks/229389/untitled-92=
?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWal=
l+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Untitled #92
(two examples have sold for more than $2 million at auction); or a Nicolas =
Party landscape ( https://manuela-nyc.com/journal/nicolas-party/?utm_campai=
gn=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustom=
er.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) (a similar work made $3.2 million at =
auction three years ago). You can spend an hour or more looking at that Lou=
ise Bourgeois spider, the Mika Rottenberg vine-and-recycled-plastic chandel=
ier and candelabra at the bar, or the Pat
Steir painting in the private dining room, where you=E2=80=99ll eat off a R=
ashid Johnson mosaic piece.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In short, the place lets the art creep up on you and hit you when you least=
 expect it, which is the kind of experience that you can=E2=80=99t get anyw=
here else=E2=80=94not at a gallery or a museum=E2=80=94unless you happen to=
 own art yourself.=C2=A0And that=E2=80=99s the point. At Manuela, the art i=
s the
experience.=C2=A0

The Clubhouse
-------------

I was reminded of all of this as I
read ( https://www.grubstreet.com/article/manuela-artfarm-hauser-and-wirth-=
nyc-restaurant-review.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F5=
%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F22%2F24%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
New York=E2=80=99s review of the restaurant, which dwells more on the decor=
 than the food. =E2=80=9COh, right=E2=80=94the food,=E2=80=9D wrote the mag=
azine=E2=80=99s critic, Matthew Schneier, who found many of the dishes to b=
e =E2=80=9Cless creative than their surroundings,=E2=80=9D but declared it =
=E2=80=9Cperfectly good=E2=80=9D even if it=E2=80=99s largely =E2=80=9Cexac=
tly what you would
expect=E2=80=A6 a mid-career survey of localish seasonal eateries.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The New York Manuela serves a different function than its Los Angeles cousi=
n, which acts more like a museum concession=E2=80=94think Caf=C3=A9 Sabarsk=
y at Neue Galerie, or Frenchette at the Whitney=E2=80=94an amenity that eas=
es the trip to an unfamiliar neighborhood or an intimidating institution. T=
hat open-air restaurant provides a palate cleanser for the
senses and facilitates spending a few hours in Hauser=E2=80=99s art complex=
=2E=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But here in New York, where Hauser=E2=80=99s gallery spaces are distributed=
 throughout the city=E2=80=94Chelsea, the Upper East Side, and a few steps =
north of Manuela on Wooster=E2=80=94the restaurant would ideally become a c=
lubhouse: a place where artists, collectors, advisors, and maybe even a few=
 rival dealers will congregate and table hop. That would
give the art experience authenticity and appeal.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In the meantime, Mrs. Wallpower, the art advisor, and I spent several hours=
 entertained by a charming bartender and taking side-eye notes on the hands=
y couple seated next to us. If I=E2=80=99m being honest, the bar seemed mor=
e lively than the restaurant. And the overall effect of so much art, and so=
 many art-based design objects, crammed into one experience could come acro=
ss as
contrived. That said, when I messaged the art advisor to find out what she =
thought, she told me she was going back again this week to try the food.=C2=
=A0

