itney=E2=80=94an amenity that eases the trip to an unfamiliar neighborhood =
or an intimidating institution. That open-air restaurant provides a palate =
cleanser for the
senses and facilitates spending a few hours in Hauser=E2=80=99s art complex=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But here in New York, where Hauser=E2=80=99s ga=
llery spaces are distributed throughout the city=E2=80=94Chelsea, the Upper=
 East Side, and a few steps north of Manuela on Wooster=E2=80=94the restaur=
ant would ideally become a clubhouse: a place where artists, collectors, ad=
visors, and maybe even a few rival dealers will congregate and table hop. T=
hat would
give the art experience authenticity and appeal.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">In the meantime, M=
rs. Wallpower, the art advisor, and I spent several hours entertained by a =
charming bartender and taking side-eye notes on the handsy couple seated ne=
xt to us. If I=E2=80=99m being honest, the bar seemed more lively than the =
restaurant. And the overall effect of so much art, and so many art-based de=
sign objects, crammed into one experience could come across as
contrived. That said, when I messaged the art advisor to find out what she =
thought, she told me she was going back again this week to try the food.=C2=
